# Python Backend (FastAPI + SQLAlchemy + psycopg2)

## Stack

- FastAPI + Pydantic v2
- SQLAlchemy 2.x ORM
- psycopg2 driver (`postgresql+psycopg2://`)
- Alembic migrations
- pytest for tests

## Layer rules

| Layer | Responsibility |
|-------|----------------|
| `routers/` | HTTP only — parse request, call service, return Pydantic schema |
| `services/` | Business logic, DB session usage |
| `models/` | SQLAlchemy ORM models |
| `schemas/` | Pydantic request/response (separate from models) |
| `db/session.py` | Engine, SessionLocal, `get_db` dependency |

## ORM rules

- Use SQLAlchemy 2.0 style (`Mapped`, `select()`, `db.get()`)
- Keep queries in services — not in routers
- Never return ORM models from routers; map to Pydantic schemas
- Migrations via Alembic only — no manual prod schema changes

```python
# GOOD
def get_user(db: Session, user_id: str) -> User | None:
    return db.get(User, user_id)

# BAD — exposing ORM in router
@router.get("/users/{id}")
def show(id: str, db: Session = Depends(get_db)):
    return db.get(User, id)  # returns ORM object directly
```

## Keep it simple

- Plain functions in services over deep class hierarchies
- One router file per domain
- Early returns; avoid nested session logic

## Auth dependency

Every product route (except `/health`):

1. `get_current_user` — JWT validation
2. `require_subscription("education")` — entitlement check
3. Tenant scope in service layer
